> If you ask for a traditional mole recipe, you'll get something with a very, very long list of fancy ingredients. Luckily, we've gathered everything for you and put it all into a spice blend that makes achieving mole's deep flavors a cinch. It's based around cocoa powder, cumin, chili powder, and smoked paprika, creating an earthy profile that's perfect for the ground beef in these tacos that also come with chipotle crema, poblano pepper, and corn tortillas.

Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}. Core, seed, and thinly slice @poblano pepper{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and poblano. Cook, stirring often, until just tender, ~{5-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

While poblano and onion cook, cut @heirloom grape tomatoes{4%oz} into quarters. Cut @lime{1} into wedges. Combine @sour cream{4%tbsp}, a squeeze of lime, and a pinch of @chipotle powder{1%tsp} (to taste—it's spicy) in a #small bowl{}. Season with salt and pepper.

Add @tomato paste{2%tbsp} to pan with poblano and onion. Stir until thoroughly combined. Cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add @ground beef{10%oz}, @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}, and @mole spice blend{1%tsp} to pan, breaking up meat into pieces. Cook, tossing occasionally, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Meanwhile, wrap @corn tortillas{6} in a lightly dampened #paper towel{} and microwave until warm and soft, about ~{30%seconds}.

Fill tortillas with beef mixture and tomatoes. Dollop with crema. Tear @cilantro{¼%oz} leaves from stems and scatter over top. Serve with lime wedges on the side for squeezing over.